<HEADLINE>
<P>
ROMANCE IN THE '80S 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
While Rainer can rest assured that there is no conspiracy to portray the world 
in Hollywood's image, romance is, by definition, a bit removed from reality, 
and fills an important need. 
</P>
<P>
Love, a deeper concept Ranier avoided entirely, was depicted in most of the 
films he criticized. Love works, and it's a lot more mature than romance. 
</P>
<P>
Ranier believes optimism recalls a bygone era, but perhaps the author is stuck 
back in the bra-burning, sexual-war era and its immediate aftermath, which are 
both passe. 
</P>
<P>
JAMES TUGEND 
</P>
<P>
Los Angeles 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Letter to the Editor 
</P>
</TYPE>
