</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
HINTS FROM HELOISE: EVEN MORE USES FOR WHITE VINEGAR 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DEAR HELOISE: I've always known white vinegar can be useful for many things, 
but never realized there are hundreds of uses. I'd like to pass on a few. 
</P>
<P>
Did you know that most decals and stickers on windows can be removed by putting 
vinegar on them? Paint a few coats on, let soak for a few minutes and the 
stickers will wash off easily. 
</P>
<P>
My husband's lunch box started getting a terrible odor, so I dampened a piece 
of bread with vinegar and put it in the lunch box overnight. I washed it the 
next morning and was surprised to see how fresh-smelling it was. 
</P>
<P>
One more thing I did with vinegar was remove new deodorant stains from my 
husband's shirts. All I did was rub the area before washing them. I'm so happy 
with it I always keep a gallon handy. 
</P>
<P>
 -- M. B., Rochester, N.Y. 
</P>
<P>
DEAR HELOISE: I have a shelf full of cookbooks and always had a tough time 
remembering which one contained that scrumptious recipe I discovered six months 
ago. Now I have an address book on the shelf with my cookbooks and use it as a 
directory. I list my favorite recipes in alphabetical order and note the name 
of the cookbook it's in and the page number. 
</P>
<P>
 -- BEVERLY, Dallas 
</P>
<P>
DEAR HELOISE: Your hints have saved me lots of money and now I'd like to share 
one. When your celery gets wilted and limp, don't throw it away. Just put the 
stalks in cold water and they will crisp up again. Use right away or keep in 
the fridge for a day or two. 
</P>
<P>
If there's too much to use this way, don't throw it out. Dice it up and cook it 
in a little water until it's just tender. Cool, divide it into small amounts 
and freeze. It's great to have on hand for soups and casseroles. 
</P>
<P>
 -- HAZEL, Aberdeen, S.D. 
</P>
<P>
DEAR HELOISE: We keep a magnetic note pad on the refrigerator. The pads with 
the magnet attached are very expensive, so after buying one I pulled the magnet 
off the cardboard and glued it on a regular note pad. I've now used the same 
magnet for over a year and saved quite a few pennies. 
</P>
<P>
 -- LIZ, Ohio 
</P>
<P>
DEAR HELOISE: Pot holders sure get dirty quickly in my home. It seems they are 
always in the washing machine. 
</P>
<P>
A friend suggested the following to me. When taking the pot holders out of the 
dryer, spray them liberally with a fabric protector and then use them. They 
stay cleaner a lot longer. 
</P>
<P>
 -- BETSY, Las Vegas 
</P>
</TEXT>
