<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE CURTAIN RISES: EASTERN EUROPE, 1989; 
</P>
<P>
VOICES; 
</P>
<P>
'I PRAY GORBACHEV WILL STAY ALIVE' 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Andras Szilagyi heads the psychiatric department at Tetenyi Hospital in 
Budapest. He is also a member of the opposition group Hungarian Democratic 
Forum. 
</P>
<P>
"Every night I get down on my knees and I pray that Gorbachev will stay alive 
six more months, one more year, so that we can push these reforms through so 
there is no turning back." 
</P>
<P>
He also has misgivings about the commitment of his compatriots: 
</P>
<P>
"Hungarians have had a life without any political ideas, and now they're not 
interested in politics, they don't want to speak, they're just interested in 
consumer ideas and their standard of living. 
</P>
<P>
"It's a collective depression. Hungary has lost two world wars, two-thirds of 
its population. We live in a political system we don't like, with economic 
standards that go down step by step. 
</P>
<P>
"The real changes will come when the average man learns to think in political 
terms and not Frigidaires." 
</P>
</TEXT>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
EASTERN EUROPE -- GOVERNMENT; HUNGARY -- GOVERNMENT; GOVERNMENT REFORM 
</P>
</SUBJECT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
