<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE CHALLENGE OF THE BATTLEFIELD; 
</P>
<P>
LEADERSHIP IS THE GOAL FOR CADETS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By James Robbins 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The soldiers lay in shallow foxholes on a recent warm, windy morning, eating 
chicken a la king and pork patties from plastic envelopes and waiting for the 
enemy. 
</P>
<P>
The enemy began to appear on the far ridge. Thirty or 40 soldiers appeared at 
the top of the hill. The troops in the foxholes talked about wiping them out 
with one mortar round -- but they had no mortars. 
</P>
<P>
After all, the ROTC cadets didn't want to touch off a brush fire from sparks 
and flames coming out of their rifles, and they certainly didn't want to kill 
each other. 
</P>
<P>
They and the attacking "army" were participating in a simulated attack -- an 
"airmobile insertion" -- as part of a weekend training venture at Camp 
Pendleton in San Diego County for ROTC cadets stationed at Cal State Fullerton, 
Claremont College, Cal State San Bernardino and Cal Poly Pomona. 
</P>
<P>
"If we can teach them to take 40 people and take that hill, we can teach them 
to run a finance division," said Army Maj. Kenneth Sadekas, who runs the ROTC 
program at Cal State Fullerton. 
</P>
<P>
"Leadership is the primary goal here," said Army Capt. Jack Roberts, who 
teaches in the ROTC program at Claremont. "The real skills are thinking, making 
plans and making decisions." He said the cadets are not only getting a college 
education but they are also learning leadership skills that most students don't 
get until they are out of school. James Robbins 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Cadet Mark Graham, in charge of Blue platoon, listens during briefing. ; 
Photo, Cadet members of the Blue platoon, silhouetted against a brightening 
sky, stand in loose formation on a hilltop while waiting to be briefed on what 
they have to do during the day's exercise. ; Photo, Cadet Mark Graham, above, 
urges troops to board a helicopter kicking up a cloud of dust. ; Photo, At the 
end of the second day, Graham wipes the grime off his face as he relaxes, far 
right. ; Photo, Another cadet, right, labors to dig a foxhole. STEVE TOWNSLEY / 
Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
RESERVE OFFICERS TRAINING CORPS; MILITARY MANEUVERS 
</P>
</SUBJECT>
</DOC>
